:  French Collette.","French; English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places in Calvados and Seine-Maritime named Carville, from the Scandinavian personal name <i>Kári</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> or <b>Mac Cearbhaill</b>, see   Carroll  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carroll","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> or <b>Mac Cearbhaill</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Cearbhall</i>’, a personal name perhaps based on <i>cearbh</i> ‘hacking’ and hence originally a byname for a butcher or a fierce warrior.","English and Scottish: variant of   Carrell  ."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"Petronilla","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old female name; an Italian diminutive formed from Pietro, i.e. Peter."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":86,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":95,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","descri